      <div rendition="class:83225 maturity:83211" type="edition" xml:lang="san-Latn">
        <div n="A" type="textpart">
          <head xml:lang="eng">Seal</head>
          <!--
The seal inscription is "so worn out, that nothing of it can be read except a few disconnected letters here and there, and Sam(u)drag(u)p(taḥ), very faintly, at the end of line 5" (Bhandarkar 1981:229). Bhandarkar supposes the legend would have been a succinct genealogy.
-->
          <p><lb n="1"/><gap extent="unknown" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
<lb n="2"/><gap extent="unknown" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
<lb n="3"/><gap extent="unknown" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
<lb n="4"/><gap extent="unknown" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
<lb n="5"/><gap extent="unknown" reason="illegible" unit="character"/> sam<unclear>u</unclear>drag<unclear>u</unclear>p<unclear>taḥ</unclear>
</p>
        </div>
        <div n="B" type="textpart">
          <head xml:lang="eng">Plates</head>
          <p><lb n="1"/><g type="mangala"/>svasti mahā-nau-hasty-aśva-jaya-skandhāvārā<choice>
              <sic>jā</sic>
              <corr>d a</corr>
            </choice>yoddhyā-vāsakāt-sarvva-rājocchettu<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> pr̥<!--
The mangala symbol is different from that on the Nalanda plate, resembling an L with a curved bottom. The symbol is not even mentioned, just transcribed as oṁ by Bhandarkar. Sircar says it's siddham.
--><!--
°āvārāj On the plate the letter is quite damaged, but to me does not look at all like the ja in jayaskandhā°. If indeed ja, is this perhaps an indication that the town name was also changed by the man who copied the plate?
--><lb break="no" n="2"/>thivyām apratirathasya catur-udadhi-salilāsvādita-yaśa<supplied reason="omitted">so</supplied>dhanada-varuṇendrā<lb break="no" n="3"/>ntaka-samasya kr̥tānta-paraśor nyāyāgatāneka-go-hiraṇya-koṭi-pradasya ciroccha<lb break="no" n="4"/>nnāśvamedhāharttu<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> mahārāja-śrī-gupta-prapauttrasya mahārāja-śrī-ghaṭotkaca-pauttrasya
<lb n="5"/>mahārājādhirāja-śrī-candragupta-puttrasya licchivi-dauhittrasya mahāde-vyā<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ṁ</supplied> ku<lb break="no" n="6"/>māradevyām utpanna<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> parama-bhāgavato mahārājādhirāja-śrī-samudra<lb break="no" n="7"/>guptaḥ gayā-vaiṣayika-revatikā-grāme vrāhmaṇa-puroga-grāma-vala<lb break="no" n="8"/>tkauṣabhyām āha<unclear>|</unclear>
</p>
          <p>eva cārtha<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ṁ</supplied> viditam bo bhavatv e<choice>
              <sic>ś</sic>
              <corr>ṣ</corr>
            </choice>a grāmo mayā mātā-pittror ā<lb break="no" n="9"/>tmanaś ca puṇyābhivr̥ddhaye bhāradvāja-sagotrāya vahvr̥cāya sa<unclear>vra</unclear>hmacā<!--
according to Bhandarkar's translation, bahvr̥ca is a śākhā, and so he takes savrahmacārin as the king's (?) "religious fellow-student".
--><lb break="no" n="10"/>riṇe vrāhmaṇa-gomadevasvāmine soparikaroddeśenāgrahāratvenāti<!--
Bhandarkar reads gopadeva, his editor's note (p230n13) says the reading is gomadeva. I concur.
--><!--
Bhandarkar prints s-oparika-oddeśen°, but this is clearly a typo, the character ro is there.
--><lb break="no" n="11"/>sr̥ṣṭaḥ tad yuṣmābhir asya śrotavyam ājñā ca karttavyā sarvve ca samucitā grāma-pra<!--
Bhandarkar remarks that ca samucitā was first engraved as sa camucitā; this is plausible, but perhaps equally plausible is that samu was engraved first, then corrected to casa and continued with mucitā.
--><lb break="no" n="12"/>tyayāmeya-hiraṇyādayo deyāḥ na <sic>cetat</sic>-prabhr̥ty etad-āgrahārikeṇ<choice>
              <sic>a</sic>
              <corr>ā</corr>
            </choice>nyad-grā<!--
Both Bhandarkar and Lielukhine print a space before meya, but to me this seems like āmeya in cpd with the previous and qualifying hiraṇyādayo. Pratyaya is, really pratyaya, not pratyāya as in Nalanda plate.
--><!--
cetat sic, corr caitat, says Bhandarkar, but compare Nalanda (%IN00003/8), cetat is probably a misreading (by the forger) of cetaf (ca itaḥ) in the original.
--><!--
I'm pretty sure it's anyaṅgrāma rather than anyadgrāma in fact, which may result from a copying of anyagrāma with an accidental dot over the nya read by the forger as an anusvāra.
--><lb break="no" n="13"/>mādi-karada-kuṭumbi-kārukādayaḥ praveśayitavyā <choice>
              <sic>ma</sic>
              <corr>a</corr>
            </choice>nyathā niyatam āgra<lb break="no" n="14"/>hārākṣepa<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ḥ</supplied> syād iti
</p>
          <p>sambaT <num value="9">9</num> vaiśākha di <num value="10">
              <g type="numeral">10</g>
            </num><!--
for sambat Bhandarkar prints samat (corr. samvat), but the b is clearly there so this is a typo.
--><lb n="15"/>Anya-grāmākṣapaṭalādhikr̥ta-dyūta-gopasvāmy-ādeśa-likhitaḥ<!--
why dyūta? Bhandarkar simply "translates" it as dūtaka
--></p>
